> /usr/local/opt/podman/libexec

@Dr0p42 

Can you try uninstalling and reinstalling podman using brew, verifying it works, and then try running the compiled binary? Also, please try using this branch as it's based off of the stable v.34: https://github.com/philnalwalker/podman/tree/9pfs-v3.4 Thanks!

@philnalwalker, you're the man!
podman version 3.4.5-dev works much better! I successfully tested Podman-compose and port forwarding (@jeesmon)
Will keep testing and reporting.

> I would not suggest mounting /lib/modules as a remote filesystem, it was supposed to be the kernel modules on the VM.

@philnalwalker Is there anything we can do about it in your patch to podman?

Looks like exclude `/lib` here? https://github.com/philnalwalker/podman/blob/27296c53a852ac2e036a467055ffe1b7e8357db4/cmd/podman/containers/run.go#L164-L166

UPDATE: Able to start Kind cluster with the following change in cmd/podman/containers/run.go b/cmd/podman/containers/run.go

```
-			if strings.HasPrefix(volume, "/") {
+			if strings.HasPrefix(volume, "/") && !strings.HasPrefix(volume, "/lib") {
```

Still hitting some network issues when connecting to cluster using `kubectl`

> I had to abandon those instructions as the step that requires me to run brew install --build-from-source homebrew-qemu-9p/Formula/qemu.rb wanted a github login and authentication kept failing even though I used the correct password; something about needing a personal access token. So not sure how the .rb is running but this doesn't work for me.

@jmb-missionlane That step is not needed, actually. Previous step 5 installed it for me. See https://github.com/containers/podman/issues/8016#issuecomment-1034918559

@philnalwalker Can you please confirm if Step 6 is really needed. If you not, could you please edit your instructions?

@baude right. of course -- sorry, in my head I was thinking about this needing to be for a package that lives in CoreOS, since that was an issue for some other mac podman issues I had before.

My recommendation, then, is that for now this stays living as a floating patchset for people's use cases for another week or two. The qemu maintainer who handles 9pfs stuff is working on merging another set of changes this week, and we'll reevaluate next week how these changes are relative to those. I'm quite confident that this will end up in 7.0 one way or another, but I don't want to start pinging the brew maintainers to merge in the patchset JUST yet since it might still shift around a little bit, and I think it'll make it into master pretty soon.

AFAIK nix will be handling it the same way. They won't merge these changes into their qemu derivation until it's accepted upstream.

@baude I've been so deep in the qemu patch set that I've let most of the actual podman discussion breeze me by.

We're talking about https://github.com/containers/podman/pull/11454, right?

I see that [up earlier](https://github.com/containers/podman/pull/11454/files#diff-4a3677ed5171641eba40e911f19bbf5970550a9e1ce75a30959e6c8032b2e39cR210-R217) qemu is being called with virtfs, but it does seem like podman is still choosing how to use the mount commands on the coreos side [a little further down](https://github.com/containers/podman/pull/11454/files#diff-4a3677ed5171641eba40e911f19bbf5970550a9e1ce75a30959e6c8032b2e39cR402-R404). Can podman just set the uids there?
